States","of,Northop,Flintshire,Wales":"Northop, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","of,,Flintshire,Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Madog","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French Canadian: variant of   Madore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Madore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Eusebe, Fernand, Lucien, Normand, Adhemar, Adrien, Donat, Elzear, Francois, Gaetan, Gilles.","French Canadian: from a French shortened form of the Spanish personal name <i>Amador</i>, from Latin <i>Amator</i> (from <i>amator</i> ‘lover’), a Christian saint's name. Compare   Mador  .","In some cases possibly also Breton (<b>Madoré</b>): nickname meaning literally ‘good help’, from Old Breton <i>mat</i> ‘good’ and <i>uuoret</i> ‘help’."]}]},{"name":"Ithel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: compound of <i>iud</i> ‘lord, prince’ + <i>hael</i> ‘generous’; borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by the son of Llarian."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ithel ap Madog was born about 1315, in Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Madog Ap Howel Gymer, was 16 and his mother, Gwenllian verch Lloyd, was 16. He had at least 1 son with ap Madog."},"et":{"about 1315–":"umbes 1315–Surnud","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1345–1392":"1345–1392","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1337–Male":"1337–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1300–1320":"1300–1320","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","about 1315":"umbes 1315","about 1337":"umbes 1337","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","ABT    1370":"umbes 1370","about 1330":"umbes 1330","1370":"1370","1392":"1392","of,Tegeingl ctf,Flintshire,Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","{Lln Eurd